<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,474,499]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: The new subspecies differs mainly from the nominate subspecies by having larger teeth and teeth intervals, and low number of teeth in stridulatory file of male. Compared to the nominate subspecies, the calling song of the new subspecies is easily distinguished by a smaller number impulses and typical decrescendo pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,553,582,607]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Description: Male (
<typeStatus box="[430,540,582,607]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">holotype</typeStatus>
):
</emphasis>
Fastigium as wide as half of the antennal scapus, slightly narrowed frontward and faintly depressed dorsally. Pronotum slightly wider in metazona than prozona, slightly depressed at mesozona laterally; disc of pronotum with a straight frontal margin and faintly concave caudal margin (
<figureCitation box="[1201,1306,654,679]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 22. Dorsal view of pronotum. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (male); C, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (male); D, P. variicercis (male); E–F, P. salmani sp. n. (female); G, P. zonatus datca (male); I, P. variicercis (female); J–K, P. varicornis (male and female, not in scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242375/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 22G</figureCitation>
). Pronotum slightly raised backward in profile (
<figureCitation box="[566,653,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 47" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 47. Male and female habitus of Poecilimon zonatus datca ssp. n. from Datça (Muğla).A–B, males; C, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242425/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
). Tegmina with black longutidunal band, slightly rounded at caudal parts and extends beyond middle of first abdominal tergite. Cu2 of left tegmen roundly projecting at right margin (
<figureCitation box="[159,269,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 22. Dorsal view of pronotum. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (male); C, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (male); D, P. variicercis (male); E–F, P. salmani sp. n. (female); G, P. zonatus datca (male); I, P. variicercis (female); J–K, P. varicornis (male and female, not in scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242375/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 22G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[289,375,763,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 47" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 47. Male and female habitus of Poecilimon zonatus datca ssp. n. from Datça (Muğla).A–B, males; C, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242425/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">47A–B</figureCitation>
). Hindfemur without spines. Epiproct transversely enlarged. Cerci gradually narrowing distalwards, distal 1/3–1/4 obtusely incurved and slightly tapered apically; there are two rows of denticles distally, preapical row includes 1, subapical row includes 5–6 denticles (
<figureCitation box="[865,984,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1927,1949]" captionTargetBox="[311,1275,193,1906]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[311,1275,193,1906]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 23. Dorsal view of male cerci.A–H, P.z. zonatus (A, Beydağ, B–C, Bozkır, D–E, Ermenek; F, Esencik, G, Munzur); I–J, P.z. datcassp.n. (Datça)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242377/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<date box="[917,956,835,859]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="1923-01">23I</date>
–J
</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate wide at proximal part, obtusely narrowed at caudal part, with slightly sinuate and almost straight caudal margin (
<figureCitation box="[1159,1263,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[304,1291,194,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[303,1291,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 10. Subgenital plate of the males. A, P.tauricola; B–C, P. azizsancar sp. n.; E–G, P. variicercis; H–I, P. salmani sp. n.; J–N, P.z. zonatus; O, P.z. datca ssp. n." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242357/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 10O</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,400,906,931]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Stridulatory file:</emphasis>
Male stridulatory file is similar to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="zonatus Bolivar" authorityYear="1899" box="[798,938,908,931]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="zonatus" subSpecies="zonatus">
<emphasis box="[798,938,908,931]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. z. zonatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general structure, but is distinguished by low number of teeth which are sparsely arranged and relatively larger than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="zonatus Bolivar" authorityYear="1899" box="[1053,1196,943,966]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="zonatus" subSpecies="zonatus">
<emphasis box="[1053,1196,943,966]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. z. zonatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1213,1320,942,967]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1386,1408]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1436,265,1365]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 17. Stridulatory file on underside of left tegmen of males. A–C, P. zonatus zonatus (A–B, Erzincan; C, Malatya); D, P. zonatus datca; E–J, P. variicercis (E–G, Erzurum, Şenkaya; H, Erzurum, İnceçay (type locality); I, Erzurum, Uğurlu; J, Erzurum, between Olur–Oltu)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242369/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 17D</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation box="[1334,1421,942,967]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,239,1530,1553]" captionText="TABLE 3. Measurement of stridulatory file of the species (no data available for P.varicornis)." pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Table 3</tableCitation>
). Tooth morphology is clearly different from other species of the group (
<figureCitation box="[944,1048,978,1003]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1927,1949]" captionTargetBox="[321,1261,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[321,1263,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 18. Medial teeth of stridulatory file at higher magnification. A–D, P. zonatus zonatus (A, Erzincan; B, Konya, Taşkent; C, Ermenek; D, Konya, Bozkır); E–F, P. variicercis (E, Erzurum, İnceçay (type locality); F, Erzurum, Şenkaya); G, P. zonatus datca ssp. n.; H, P.salmani sp. n.; I–J, P.vodnensis; K–L, P.salmani." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242371/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,356,1014,1039]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Bioacoustics:</emphasis>
The calling song is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName box="[775,913,1014,1039]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vodnensis">
<emphasis box="[775,913,1014,1039]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. vodnensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the calling songs of the only two males we have studied, the “click”-like syllable are presented in small groups which were repeated in large, irregular intervals (
<figureCitation box="[262,346,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1696,1718]" captionTargetBox="[170,1385,219,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[151,1436,193,1675]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 30. Structure of male calling songs of P. salmani sp. n., P.zonatus datca ssp. n. and P.variicercis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242391/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). The syllables lasted about 9.4 ms and were composed of about 3–4 impulses (
<figureCitation box="[1230,1313,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1724,1746]" captionTargetBox="[326,1253,207,1683]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[302,1284,193,1702]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 37. The oscillograms and spectral view of the male calling songs of P. zonatus datca and P.vodnensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242405/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
). The peak frequency of the song had a maximum at about 28 kHz (see for details 
<tableCitation box="[946,1030,1122,1147]" captionStart="TABLE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,239,152,175]" captionText="TABLE 4. Descriptive statistics for examined characters of male calling songs (data given as averages, additionally" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Table 4</tableCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1043,1126,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1724,1746]" captionTargetBox="[326,1253,207,1683]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[302,1284,193,1702]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 37. The oscillograms and spectral view of the male calling songs of P. zonatus datca and P.vodnensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242405/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,295,1158,1183]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Female:</emphasis>
Pronotum laterally wider than in male, metazona slightly wider than prozona, strongly depressed (
<figureCitation box="[159,262,1194,1219]" captionStart="FIGURE 47" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 47. Male and female habitus of Poecilimon zonatus datca ssp. n. from Datça (Muğla).A–B, males; C, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242425/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 47C</figureCitation>
). Tegmina short, slightly extending beyond posterior margin of the pronotum, fully overlapping dorsally. Subgenital plate triangular (
<figureCitation box="[463,568,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 12. Subgenital plate, gonangulum and lamella from below. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (Dalyan); C, P. variicercis (Olur, İnceçay), D, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (Datça), E–G, P. zonatus zonatus, H, P. tauricola (Bolkar Mts.), I, P. azizsancar sp. n. (Uzundere, Dikyar)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242361/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 12D</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor, gonangulum and lamella as in 
<figureCitation box="[1063,1176,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 12. Subgenital plate, gonangulum and lamella from below. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (Dalyan); C, P. variicercis (Olur, İnceçay), D, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (Datça), E–G, P. zonatus zonatus, H, P. tauricola (Bolkar Mts.), I, P. azizsancar sp. n. (Uzundere, Dikyar)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242361/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs. 12D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[1187,1236,1231,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1912,1934]" captionTargetBox="[188,1400,733,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[188,1400,733,1891]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 28. Ovipositor shapes of PZG. A–D, P. z. zonatus (A, Erzincan; B, Malatya; C, Ermenek; D, Konya); E–F, P. variicercis; G, P.z. datcassp.n.; H, P.salmani, sp. n.." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242387/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">28G</figureCitation>
